istently sought or acknowledged, and they are still often marginalised in healthcare encounters. Drawing on original research and a diverse range of practice examples, Brady explores the potential for inclusive and diverse approaches to young people’s participation in health services from the perspectives of young people, health professionals and other practitioners. She presents a practical new framework, embedded in children’s rights, that shows how young people’s participation can be integrated into services in ways that are meaningful, effective and sustainable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAffleck, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAinsworth, Jenny (Sammy), econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAinsworth, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, Louca-Mai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, Louca-Mai, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Chloe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairns, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChallinor, Robyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClapham, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Kath, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeltham, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagell, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHathway, Felicity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Lizzy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKendal, Sarah, eco